  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Preface to Seeing Off Counselor Shin on His Journey North
  author: Lee Je-hyeon
  language: eng
  text: |-
    A scholar's journey through the world is like a vessel upon the water. His talent becomes the mast, his destiny becomes the favorable wind—only then can he reach his destination. Yet talent and destiny alone are not enough. If his aspirations are base, then though the mast stands firm and the wind blows fair, if the helmsman lacks true character, how can he bear ten thousand measures of cargo or traverse ten thousand leagues to cross what lies beyond reach?

    Counselor Shin has since his youth devoted himself to learning, keen of mind and eager in inquiry. His brush and ink flourish across the page, his mastery of records and documents knows no bounds—truly, he possesses great talent. Within mere years of entering service, he has risen through the ranks of Provincial Lecturer and Royal Secretary, advanced to Vice Director of the Secretariat, and become a Court Gentleman of the Eastern Province—truly, he is blessed by fortune. Drawing upon his old friendships, he has elevated worthy men to high office, consulted with the wise and aged to ensure harmonious governance, corrected the ruler with integrity, and treated all visitors with sincere devotion—truly, he possesses noble purpose. Now summoned as an imperial official and preparing to journey west with honors, his rare talent, open fortune, and great aspirations shall be revealed all the more.

    Twenty-eight worthy gentlemen, led by Kwon Chan-seon, have woven verses together in celebration of his departure, following the rhyme scheme of Cheng Yuggu's parting poem, and have asked me to compose this preface. I come forward with cup in hand to complete the discourse on vessels.

    Though rivers and seas differ greatly in size, the vessel that sails upon them operates by the same principles. To raise the mast and unfurl the sail—this is to advance. To cast the anchor and secure the rope—this is to hold steady. And there must be cloth patches too, to prepare for leaks and dampness. A kingdom is like a river, the realm of the Son of Heaven like the vast ocean. The Counselor's vessel journeys from the rivers to the sea. If he can make Righteousness his mast, Trustworthiness his sail, Propriety his rope, Wisdom his anchor, and Reverence, Prudence, Integrity, and Diligence his patches, then what cargo cannot he bear? What distance cannot he traverse? What impassable strait cannot he cross?

    Once Tian Shu and Han Anguo, though servants of Liang and Zhao, took their place in the Han court, earning renown in their time and leaving their names to posterity. This is what I hope for Counselor Shin.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Ten thousand measures (萬斛) and ten thousand leagues (萬里) are hyperbolic expressions in classical Chinese for vast quantities and immense distances.
  - key: ''
    value: 'The metaphor of a vessel with its mast, sail, anchor, and rope—and cloth patches for repairs—represents the virtues and qualities necessary for a statesman: Righteousness, Trustworthiness, Propriety, Wisdom, and the practical virtues of Reverence, Prudence, Integrity, and Diligence.'
  - key: ''
    value: Tian Shu and Han Anguo were Han Dynasty officials from the kingdoms of Liang and Zhao who rose to prominence in the central imperial court, serving as historical exemplars of capable ministers who advanced through merit.
